{{refimprove|date=July 2012}}
"'''Frankly, my dear, I don't give a damn'''" is a line from the 1939 film ''[[Gone with the Wind (film)|Gone with the Wind]]'' starring [[Clark Gable]] and [[Vivien Leigh]]. The line is spoken by [[Rhett Butler]] (Gable), as his last words to [[Scarlett O'Hara]] (Leigh), in response to her tearful question: "Where shall I go? What shall I do?" Scarlett clings to the hope that she can win him back. This line is also partially spoken by Rhett Butler in Margaret Mitchell's novel ''[[Gone with the Wind (novel)|Gone with the Wind]]'', published in 1936, from which the film is derived.
The line demonstrates that Rhett has finally given up on Scarlett and their tumultuous relationship. After more than a decade of fruitlessly seeking her love, he no longer cares what happens to her.
This quotation was [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Movie Quotes|voted the number one movie line]] of all time by the [[American Film Institute]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|title=AFI's 100 YEARS...100 MOVIE QUOTES|url=http://www.afi.com/100years/quotes.aspx|publisher=American Film Institute|accessdate=11 May 2013|date=21 June 2005}}</ref>
==Production code conflict== Prior to the film's release, censors objected to the use of the word "damn" in the film, a word that had been prohibited by the 1930 [[Motion Picture Production Code]], beginning in July 1934. However, before 1930 the word "damn" had been relatively common in films. In the silent era, [[John Gilbert (actor)|John Gilbert]] even shouted "Goddamn you!" to the enemy during battle in ''[[The Big Parade]]'' (1925). The Production Code was ratified on March 31, 1930, and was effective for motion pictures whose filming began afterward. Thus, [[Sound film|talkies]] that used "damn" include ''Glorifying the American Girl'' (1929), ''Flight'' (1929), ''[[Gold Diggers of Broadway]]'' (1929), ''Hell's Angels'' (1930), ''The Big Trail'' (1930), ''The Dawn Patrol'' (1930), ''The Green Goddess'' (1930) and ''Dracula'' (1931). Although legend persists that the Hays Office fined producer David O. Selznick $5,000 for using the word "damn", in fact the MPPDA board passed an amendment to the Production Code a month and a half before the film's release, on November 1, 1939, that allowed use of the words "hell" or "damn" when their use "shall be essential and required for portrayal, in proper historical context, of any scene or dialogue based upon historical fact or folklore...or a quotation from a literary work, provided that no such use shall be permitted which is intrinsically objectionable or offends good taste".<ref>{{cite book|last=Lewis|first=Jon|title=Hollywood V. Hard Core: How the Struggle Over Censorship Saved the Modern Film Industry|year=2000|publisher=New York University Press|isbn=0814751423|page=305|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4OBepfVJOeEC&pg=PA305&lpg=PA305&dq=shall+be+essential+and+required+for+portrayal,+in+proper+historical+context,+of+any+scene+or+dialogue+based+upon+historical+fact+or+folklore...or+a+quotation+from+a+literary+work,+provided+that+no+such+use+shall+be+permitted+which+is+intrinsically+objectionable+or+offends+good+taste.&source=bl&ots=GPt2DpnROP&sig=G0B9hl_qiP8KZeHGSy_4pds8YSM&hl=en&sa=X&ei=6sWNUaHOO4Sm8ATCmYC4BQ&ved=0CGUQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=shall%20be%20essential%20and%20required%20for%20portrayal%2C%20in%20proper%20historical%20context%2C%20of%20any%20scene%20or%20dialogue%20based%20upon%20historical%20fact%20or%20folklore...or%20a%20quotation%20from%20a%20literary%20work%2C%20provided%20that%20no%20such%20use%20shall%20be%20permitted%20which%20is%20intrinsically%20objectionable%20or%20offends%20good%20taste.&f=false}}</ref> With that amendment, the [[Production Code Administration]] had no further objection to Rhett's closing line. It is actually the second use of "damn" in the film. The term "damn Yankees" is heard in the parlor scene at [[Twelve Oaks]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=POCOWATCHIT|first1=ROD|title=‘Gone With the Wind’ made history in more ways than one|url=http://www.kansas.com/entertainment/movies-news-reviews/movie-maniac/article3665379.html|accessdate=15 February 2017|work=The Wichita Eagle|date=8 Nov 2014}}</ref>
